 of Stillingia annua are ursolic acid, beta-sitosterol, and quercetin, which exhibit potent anti-inflammatory and antioxidant properties. Ursolic acid has been shown to inhibit the production of pro-inflammatory enzymes, such as COX-2 and LOX, thereby reducing inflammation. Beta-sitosterol has been found to have immunomodulatory effects, modulating the immune response and reducing inflammation. Quercetin, a flavonoid, has been demonstrated to scavenge free radicals and inhibit the activity of pro-inflammatory enzymes, such as NF-\u03baB, thereby reducing oxidative stress and inflammation. These constituents work synergistically to provide the healing benefits of Stillingia annua, making it a valuable plant for the treatment of various inflammatory and oxidative stress-related disorders.", "herb_names_common": [{"name": "queen's delight", "mentions": 9, "confidence_score": 81, "total_score": 729}, {"name": "queen's root", "mentions": 10, "confidence_score": 77, "total_score": 770}, {"name": "american stillingia", "mentions": 13, "confidence_score": 76, "total_score": 988}, {"name": "queen's thief", "mentions": 5, "confidence_score": 44, "total_score": 220}, {"name": "yellowroot", "mentions": 5, "confidence_score": 39, "total_score": 195}, {"name": "two-leaved queen's delight", "mentions": 4, "confidence_score": 25, "total_score": 100}, {"name": "king's cure", "mentions": 3, "confidence_score": 25, "total_score": 75}, {"name": "yellow root", "mentions": 3, "confidence_score": 23, "total_score": 69}, {"name": "american queen's root", "mentions": 3, "confidence_score": 21, "total_score": 63}, {"name": "bartlett's bloodroot", "mentions": 3, "confidence_score": 20, "total_score": 60}, {"name": "queen's crown", "mentions": 2, "confidence_score": 17, "total_score": 34}, {"name": "king's root", "mentions": 2, "confidence_score": 17, "total_score": 34}, {"name": "stinking willie", "mentions": 2, "confidence_score": 16, "total_score": 32}, {"name": "two-leaved stillingia", "me